[h2]Namespaces[/h2]

When you create a blank project, it has the following structure: [code format="cs" ]using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Text;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

[b]namespace [/b]SoloLearn {
  class Program {
    static void Main(string[] args) {
    }
  }
}[/code]
Note, that our whole program is inside a [b]namespace[/b]. So, what are namespaces?
Namespaces declare a scope that contains a set of related objects. You can use a namespace to organize code elements. You can define your own namespaces and use them in your program. 
The [b]using[/b] keyword states that the program is using a given namespace. 
For example, we are using the [b]System[/b] namespace in our programs, which is where the class [b]Console[/b] is defined: [code format="cs" codeId="904"][b]using [/b]System;
...
Console.WriteLine("Hi");[/code]
Without the [b]using[/b] statement, we would have to specify the namespace wherever it is used: [code format="cs" codeId="905"]System.Console.WriteLine("Hi");[/code]
[note]The .NET Framework uses namespaces to organize its many classes. [b]System [/b]is one example of a .NET Framework namespace.
Declaring your own namespaces can help you group your class and method names in larger programming projects.[/note]
